Headlines.SeoHeadline: The Morning Ledger: IPO Activity Revs Up
Headlines.Author: David Hall
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: IPO Activity Revs Up

PARAGRAPH.#text:
All eyes on Yelp today as it makes its trading debut after pricing its IPO at $15 a share -- above its expected range. The company raised $107.25 million, valuing it at $898.1 million. As DealBook notes, it's another big test of investor appetite for tech start-ups, but there are signs of wariness -- the valuation is a little lower than earlier estimates – and some investors have doubts about Yelp's business model. After eight years of operation, it's still not profitable. Twitter, meanwhile, is trying to mature its business before taking the IPO plunge. And as the WSJ says, it's finding it has a long way to go.
In its latest IPO watch (PDF) report, PwC says it expects to see a lot more companies go public this year. The pipeline is the largest in years and while it's still pretty tech heavy, there are also offerings planned from consumer, energy and health-care companies.
There's also diversity within the tech sector. The WSJ reports that a slew of B-to-B start-ups are the next wave of IPOs.
The day ahead. Light agenda – CFTC chief Gary Gensler and acting FDIC chairman Martin Gruenberg talk about investor and consumer protections in the changing financial marketplace at the George Washington University.
